nodes.documentation:
@dev Marks an address as being approved for transferFrom(), overwriting any previous
  approval. Settings _approved to address(0) clears all transfer approval.
  NOTE: _approve() does NOT send the Approval event. This is intentional because
  _approve() and transferFrom() are used together for putting Sneakers on auction, and
  there is no value in spamming the log with Approval events in that case.

devdoc.author: Heriberto Prieto

params._to: The address to be granted transfer approval. Pass address(0) to  clear all approvals.
params._tokenId: The ID of the Sneaker that can be transferred if this call succeeds.

pause().details: Called by any "C-Level" role to pause the contract. Used only when  a bug or exploited is detected and we need to limit damage.

setCEO(address).details: Assigns a new address to act as the CEO. Only available to the current CEO.

params._newCEO: The address of the new CEO.

setCFO(address).details: Assigns a new address to act as the CFO. Only available to the current CEO.

params._newCFO: The address of the new CFO.

setCOO(address).details: Assigns a new address to act as the COO. Only available to the current CEO.

params._newCOO: The address of the new COO.

setMetadataAddress(address).details: Set the address of the sibling contract that tracks metadata.  CEO only.

params._tokenId: The ID number of the Sneaker whose metadata should be returned.

tokensOfOwner(address).details: This method MUST NEVER be called by smart contract code. First, it's faily  expensive (it walks the sntire Sneaker array looking for sneakers belonging to the owner.,  but it also returns a dynamic array, which is only supported for web3 calls, and  not contract-to-contract calls.

params._owner: The owner whose Sneakers we are interested in.

params._to: The address of the recipient, can be a user or contract.
params._tokenId: The ID of the Sneaker to transfer.

params._from: The address that owns the Sneaker to be transferred.
params._to: The address that should take ownership of the Sneaker. Can be any address,  including the caller.
params._tokenId: The ID of the Sneaker to be transferred.

unpause().details: Unpauses the smart contract. Can only be called by the CEO, since  one reason we may pause the contract is when CFO or COO accounts are  compromised.

devdoc.title: The fact of CryptoSneakers core contract that manages ownership, ERC-721 (draft compliant).

approve(address,uint256).notice: Grant another address the right to transfer a specific Sneaker via  transferFrom(). This is preferred flow for transfering NFTs to contacts.

balanceOf(address).notice: Returns the number of Sneakers owned by a specific address.

ownerOf(uint256).notice: Returns the total number of Sneakers currently in existence.

supportsInterface(bytes4).notice: Introspection interface as per ERC-165  Returns true for any standardized interfaces implemented by this contract. We implement  ERC0165 (obviously!) and ERC-721;

tokenMetadata(uint256,string).notice: Returns a URI pointing to a metadata package for this token conforming to  ERC-721 (https://github.com/ethereum/EIPs/issues/721)

tokensOfOwner(address).notice: Returns a list of all Sneaker IDs assigned to an address.

transfer(address,uint256).notice: Transfers a Sneaker to another address. If transferring to a smart  contract be VERY CAREFUL to ensure that it is aware of ERC-721 (or  CryptoSneakers specifically) or your Sneaker may be lost forever. Seriously.

transferFrom(address,address,uint256).notice: Transfer a Sneaker owned by another address, for which the calling address  has previously been granted transfer approval by the owner.

unpause().notice: This is public rather than external so it can be called by  derived contracts.
